\faauto\ls2\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1\cgrid0 To Nic\'e6
us, Iskander had, for the first time in his life, confided much of his secret heart; and the young Prince fired at the inspiring tale.  Often they consulted over the fortunes of their country, and, excited by their mutual in
vention, at length even dared to hope that they might effect its deliverance, when Iskander was summoned to the army.  It was a mournful parting.  Both of them felt that the last few months of their lives had owed many charms to their companionship.  The 
parting of friends, united by sympathetic tastes, is always painful; and friends, unless this sympathy subsist, had much better never meet.  Iskander stepped into the ship, sorrowful, but serene; Nic\'e6
us returned to his palace moody and fretful; lost his temper with his courtiers, and, when he was alone, even shed tears.
