us, Iskander summoned some of the chief citizens of Croia to the citadel, and submitting to them his arrangements for the administration of Epirus, announced the necessity of his instant departure for a short interv
al; and the same evening, ere the moon had risen, himself and the Prince of Athens quitted the city, and proceeded in the direction of Adrianople.  They travelled with great rapidity until they reached a small town upon the frontiers, where they halted fo
r
 one day.  Here, in the Bazaar, Iskander purchased for himself the dress of an Armenian physician.  In his long dark robes, and large round cap of black wool, his face and hands stained, and his beard and mustachios shaven, it seemed impossible that be co
uld be recognised.  Nic\'e6
