ield my chance of the brighter fortune without an effort.  Once more I appeal to your pity, if not to your love.  Were Iduna mine, were she to hold out but the possibility of her being mine, there is no career, solemnly I avow what solemnly I feel, there 
i
s no career of which I could not be capable, and no condition to which I would not willingly subscribe.  But this certainty, or this contingency, I must have:  I cannot exist without the alternative.  And now upon my knees, I implore her to grant it to me
!"
