 himself for the unsatisfactory answers he received by the opinion that they had taken a different course, and the conviction that all must now be safe.  The messenger from Croia that informed Hunniades of the escape of his daughter, also solicited his ai
d in favour of Epirus against the impending invasion of the Turks, and stimulated by personal gratitude as well as by public duty, Hunniades answered the solicitation in person at the head of twenty thousand lances.
